WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.840
Hi, I'm Rich, I work at Posit, and formerly rstudio, and I work on the gt package, have

00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:16.559
been working on it for a while, and we have a great new release, 0.8, and today I'd like

00:00:16.559 --> 00:00:22.639
to show you what we improved in terms of new functions in the package, and also what we

00:00:22.639 --> 00:00:25.680
improved in terms of existing functions in the package.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:30.840
We added a bunch of great new functions to target values and do cool things like replace

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:35.639
the values of the things that were targeted, or style the cells.

00:00:35.639 --> 00:00:40.000
And the other thing is improvements to date and time formatting especially.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.080
So I'm really excited to talk about these new features, let's dive right in.

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:49.160
So the first function I want to talk about is sub underscore values, or sub values.

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:51.599
So it's essentially like a find and replace.

00:00:51.599 --> 00:00:55.959
So we have a table here, I just made that with the table function from dplyr, I'm showing

00:00:55.959 --> 00:01:02.040
you the table now in the console, and we can look at the table as it is in gt just by piping

00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:03.639
it to the gt function.

00:01:03.639 --> 00:01:07.279
So this is the table just down here, formatted as html.

00:01:07.279 --> 00:01:10.360
So we can use sub values, I'm using it three times here, but I'll show you each time I

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:13.720
use it that we can find and replace values.

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:18.959
So in the first case I'm looking for values like 74 and 500, and replacing with 150.

00:01:18.959 --> 00:01:25.080
So if I run this, this is going to change very subtly, but you'll see 150 is there now.

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:32.000
If we do the same thing with finding the letter B, and replacing with the word B, that works.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.279
It'll just skip over these numeric columns and go right to the thing that is a character

00:01:36.279 --> 00:01:37.279
column.

00:01:37.279 --> 00:01:41.639
And same thing with 800, you can replace any text, so it could be any size text, replacing

00:01:41.639 --> 00:01:45.879
the value 800 with the words 800 right here.

00:01:45.879 --> 00:01:46.879
So that's sub values.

00:01:47.199 --> 00:01:50.279
You can do quite a bit with it, you can even have patterns.

00:01:50.279 --> 00:01:54.480
If you know about regex, you'll know what this is, essentially it could be A or C or

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:59.959
E. If you find any of those, you can replace the whole cell with A's.

00:01:59.959 --> 00:02:00.959
So let's run this.

00:02:00.959 --> 00:02:07.559
You can see right here that these values right here are replaced with that replacement value.

00:02:07.559 --> 00:02:08.559
Sweet.

00:02:08.559 --> 00:02:10.520
So we can do more advanced things.

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:13.160
Use a function that you supply, for instance.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:18.479
So this is going to be values that are less than 50, and the text you're going to replace

00:02:18.479 --> 00:02:21.360
those values with is under 50.

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:24.839
So let's just run this and take a look at the result.

00:02:24.839 --> 00:02:25.839
There we are.

00:02:25.839 --> 00:02:29.559
Lots of values which are under 50 in this column, and also in the first column.

00:02:29.559 --> 00:02:34.039
It totally ignores the column which doesn't have numerical values at all, which is kind

00:02:34.039 --> 00:02:35.039
of nice.

00:02:35.039 --> 00:02:40.279
You don't have to specify which columns, it won't error on you or do weird things.

00:02:40.279 --> 00:02:41.279
So that's sub values.

00:02:41.399 --> 00:02:47.080
I want to talk about another function which is new in GT 0.8.

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:49.119
It is tab style body.

00:02:49.119 --> 00:02:53.360
Okay, so let's start with a initial table right here.

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:58.880
This is just like an example table that I use a lot in GT for examples.

00:02:58.880 --> 00:03:02.919
And what we can do now is we could do a similar sort of thing.

00:03:02.919 --> 00:03:07.800
We can find values and then style the cells that have those values.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:13.119
So these are literal values, 49, 95 and 33, 33, they exist over here.

00:03:13.119 --> 00:03:15.839
So let's actually run this and see what the result is.

00:03:15.839 --> 00:03:18.839
Okay, so we got some values which are colored in orange.

00:03:18.839 --> 00:03:23.160
That's because we have the style here set with this helper function called cell underscore

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:25.759
fill and the color of orange.

00:03:25.759 --> 00:03:31.179
So we're essentially filling those targeted cells with that styling.

00:03:31.179 --> 00:03:35.119
So we can do lots more with this, we can have multiple styles.

00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:40.279
You just enclose them in a list, we can style the text, we can style the fill of those cells

00:03:40.279 --> 00:03:44.240
that we target, we can even style the borders of those.

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:47.039
So we're doing the same thing, targeting the same values.

00:03:47.039 --> 00:03:51.240
So if I run this, you'll see that the only thing that changes is in those two cells,

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:53.240
the styling will totally change.

00:03:53.240 --> 00:03:55.039
There you go.

00:03:55.039 --> 00:03:59.360
So it's totally different styling, but targeting the same cells with these literal values.

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:00.960
So that's tab style body.

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:01.960
There's more to it.

00:04:01.960 --> 00:04:06.720
You can have sub values that I spoke about earlier, and you can have different types

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:08.919
of targets.

00:04:08.919 --> 00:04:12.080
You can target row and target column.

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:13.080
What does that do?

00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:18.200
It just means that if it finds anything, like a cell, it'll just style the entire row or

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:19.760
the entire column.

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:21.079
So let's actually take a look at that.

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:28.760
So let's do this whole statement, run it, and see here that because it found 49.95 over

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:34.320
here, and we said targets equals row, it's going to style it with cell fill color of

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:36.279
light green all the way across.

00:04:36.279 --> 00:04:43.760
So it's a good way of highlighting a row, just based on data you have, you want to highlight

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:44.760
a row.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:49.799
You can do the same thing with this statement right here, column.

00:04:49.799 --> 00:04:55.720
So it found this value, it's a little hard to read, but that's 33.33.

00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:58.799
Because we have targets equals column, we're styling the entire column.

00:04:58.799 --> 00:04:59.799
So that's what that does.

00:04:59.799 --> 00:05:08.799
I'm going to skip ahead here and move to another new function we have in GT 0.8.

00:05:08.799 --> 00:05:10.839
It's extract cells.

00:05:10.839 --> 00:05:15.880
So what it does is it allows you to pull out certain cells from a GT table.

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:19.640
So you have a GT table, but you just want like a value from that table and you want

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:21.440
to put it somewhere.

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:23.459
You can do that with this function here.

00:05:23.459 --> 00:05:25.779
So it's actually best shown in a Cordo document.

00:05:25.779 --> 00:05:29.140
I have one open right here.

00:05:29.140 --> 00:05:32.660
So what I'm doing is I'm making a giant table here.

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:37.980
And the key to this is I have a table, I saved it as such, like I assigned it to this object

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:40.820
and displaying it, but I have it assigned as an object.

00:05:40.820 --> 00:05:41.820
That's a key thing here.

00:05:41.820 --> 00:05:46.739
So what you can do in Cordo and in R Markdown is you can use inline R code.

00:05:46.739 --> 00:05:52.579
It's basically this backtick with an R and some code inside there and closing with a

00:05:52.579 --> 00:05:53.859
backtick.

00:05:53.859 --> 00:06:00.299
So that's kind of cool because we can actually take that GT table, pipe it into extract cells,

00:06:00.299 --> 00:06:02.299
pull out the cell we want.

00:06:02.299 --> 00:06:05.619
And the interesting thing about this is that cell is already fully formatted.

00:06:05.619 --> 00:06:08.820
So you'll get the same formatting in the text of your document.

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:12.739
It's a little hard to imagine that right now because we just have the source document.

00:06:12.739 --> 00:06:13.739
So let's actually render it.

00:06:14.019 --> 00:06:19.380
Going to hit the render button and then it's going to do its thing in that background jobs window.

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:23.299
And when it's done, it should appear as a preview.

00:06:23.299 --> 00:06:30.299
And the key thing is we'll see in this last paragraph that we'll have a value from the table.

00:06:30.299 --> 00:06:30.980
Okay, great.

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:33.779
So I'm going to expand this a little bit, move to the bottom.

00:06:33.779 --> 00:06:35.339
So I kept the code in here.

00:06:35.339 --> 00:06:37.140
The table should be below.

00:06:37.140 --> 00:06:37.859
Great.

00:06:37.859 --> 00:06:40.179
So I pull out a value, which is one of these fractions.

00:06:40.179 --> 00:06:42.779
It's a little bit harder to format in HTML.

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:45.940
You have to do a little bit of like tag stuff.

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:50.660
But we don't have to worry about that because we have extract cells and we pulled out the cell,

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:54.660
which is from column F underscore sold and row number 14.

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:57.059
And it's right here, 2 over 10.

00:06:57.059 --> 00:06:59.540
And that's basically this one right here.

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:00.339
So kind of nice.

00:07:00.339 --> 00:07:01.579
You didn't have to replicate that.

00:07:01.579 --> 00:07:04.220
You can use something you already have inside your document.

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:07.339
And it saves a lot of transcription problems in the future.

00:07:07.339 --> 00:07:12.140
And if this table changes, this changes accordingly, which is really cool.

00:07:12.140 --> 00:07:13.859
So that's extract cells.

00:07:13.859 --> 00:07:22.619
We have another new function in GT 0.8, and it is the one called calls align decimal.

00:07:22.619 --> 00:07:26.540
So this is like an often requested bit of functionality.

00:07:26.540 --> 00:07:29.700
So we have a table here, for instance.

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:32.059
Let's see here.

00:07:32.059 --> 00:07:33.619
Let's run this.

00:07:33.619 --> 00:07:35.899
So we're just generating a table.

00:07:35.899 --> 00:07:38.940
It's a really simple table just for demonstration purposes.

00:07:38.980 --> 00:07:42.339
And say we want to format this entire column of numbers.

00:07:42.339 --> 00:07:43.779
We want three decimal places.

00:07:43.779 --> 00:07:46.940
We want drop any trailing zeros.

00:07:46.940 --> 00:07:49.540
And that's, you know, that's pretty much it for that column.

00:07:49.540 --> 00:07:52.940
So let's actually run that little bit right there.

00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:54.980
Okay, this is great.

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:59.779
The problem is that it's a little hard to read because the decimals aren't lined up in a way that,

00:07:59.779 --> 00:08:05.019
you know, makes it easy to see what is, you know, before and after the decimal mark.

00:08:05.019 --> 00:08:06.299
And there's not always a decimal mark here.

00:08:06.299 --> 00:08:09.059
This is like a whole number with no decimal.

00:08:09.059 --> 00:08:10.019
So a little hard to read.

00:08:10.019 --> 00:08:12.619
You know, it's not impossible, but it's not, you know, it can be better.

00:08:12.619 --> 00:08:15.739
So that's where this function comes in, calls align decimal.

00:08:15.739 --> 00:08:17.579
You just run that.

00:08:17.579 --> 00:08:19.140
You can target a column, but you don't have to.

00:08:19.140 --> 00:08:26.059
It just runs across the entire table, looks for columns that have numbers formatted, and just does the thing.

00:08:26.059 --> 00:08:29.059
So let's actually run this.

00:08:29.059 --> 00:08:29.540
Great.

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:30.739
Okay, so an immediate improvement.

00:08:30.739 --> 00:08:34.460
So basically what we have now is we have the decimal running all the way down.

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:36.380
I mean, this is like a sort of extreme example.

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:39.940
We have NAs and sort of some wild values here.

00:08:39.940 --> 00:08:46.059
But the idea is that it's a little easier to read, especially if you, you know, just have a ton of these values.

00:08:46.059 --> 00:08:50.140
You just want to see what the big part is and what the small part of the number is.

00:08:50.140 --> 00:08:53.260
So that's calls align decimal, just decimal alignment.

00:08:53.260 --> 00:08:57.500
So next is information about your table.

00:08:57.500 --> 00:09:00.500
You might make a really complex table like this.

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:03.700
You know, if you're a beginner with GT, you might not know what this is.

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:04.219
That's fine.

00:09:04.219 --> 00:09:07.179
That's actually, that's actually just fine.

00:09:07.179 --> 00:09:08.500
So let's run this.

00:09:08.500 --> 00:09:10.619
Let's show the table.

00:09:10.619 --> 00:09:12.940
So it's a pretty nice looking table.

00:09:12.940 --> 00:09:22.979
We have, you know, row labels here and we have column labels across the top and a spanner that spans across two columns and some formatted values in the body.

00:09:22.979 --> 00:09:23.419
So that's great.

00:09:23.419 --> 00:09:32.619
Yeah, you might get this table or you might want to style something like, say, for instance, you know, this column or some cell in there, right?

00:09:32.619 --> 00:09:43.659
So we don't know how to do that because we need to do is you have to know the ID value of, you know, like the column and also of the row.

00:09:43.659 --> 00:09:48.820
So to help that, we have this new function called tab underscore info or tab info for short.

00:09:48.820 --> 00:09:52.539
You just pass that your GT table.

00:09:52.539 --> 00:10:00.059
And what you get is an information table that shows you what your columns are called in terms of IDs and then what the labels are.

00:10:00.059 --> 00:10:12.539
So you can sort of see what you have currently in your in your viewer in terms of what you have in your table and you make the correspondence between that and your actual like ID, which is used for styling and for things like footnotes.

00:10:12.539 --> 00:10:18.020
So we have that even the rows might be labeled differently than their ID values.

00:10:18.020 --> 00:10:20.219
And it also works for spanners as well.

00:10:20.219 --> 00:10:23.260
So wherever you have in your table, this will reveal what the ID values are.

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:29.340
And this is important because sometimes with certain functions in GT, it just creates IDs for you and you have no idea what they are.

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:31.700
So this gives them to you so you can do styling.

00:10:31.700 --> 00:10:37.419
So if you go back to your other table here, we want to style, say, for instance, this column right here.

00:10:37.419 --> 00:10:40.900
And, you know, we didn't know what this was called.

00:10:40.900 --> 00:10:47.580
For instance, we know it's actually MPGG underscore C from this table here.

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:49.059
That's what it appears to be.

00:10:49.059 --> 00:10:50.500
And that's what it is.

00:10:50.500 --> 00:10:58.700
So now if we run this, we can successfully style that entire column with a background color of light blue.

00:10:58.700 --> 00:11:03.859
Because if we just put an MPG like this, we would just get an error.

00:11:03.859 --> 00:11:10.260
The next function I want to talk about, actually it's a set of functions, have to do with the date and time formatting features in GT.

00:11:10.260 --> 00:11:14.539
We have a number of functions, format date, format time, format daytime.

00:11:14.539 --> 00:11:20.900
Those have completely been overhauled, rewritten, totally feature packed now, lots more power than before.

00:11:20.900 --> 00:11:23.900
And we hope it's actually even easier to use than before.

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:24.859
So let's get right to it.

00:11:24.859 --> 00:11:30.659
So let's start with a date time string.

00:11:30.659 --> 00:11:34.380
So we can actually format that with this other function.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:37.580
It's a variant of format date, deck format date.

00:11:37.580 --> 00:11:48.419
So it's great for examples and it's great for anything inside, you know, R Markdown or Cordo if you just need formatted values like from vectors and not from columns of values in a table.

00:11:48.419 --> 00:11:49.859
It's also good for demonstration purposes.

00:11:49.859 --> 00:11:51.140
So it has all the same features.

00:11:51.140 --> 00:11:54.900
It just works on vectors rather than columns in a table.

00:11:54.900 --> 00:11:59.619
So if we were to take our date string, what we could do is we could use a date style.

00:11:59.619 --> 00:12:04.419
And these are name styles that are available in this function and also in this function.

00:12:04.419 --> 00:12:12.059
It just allows easy access to like styling, you know, an input date time to whatever output date time.

00:12:12.059 --> 00:12:15.140
So we do the same thing for formatting times.

00:12:15.140 --> 00:12:17.700
So we're just getting the time portion of this out.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:22.500
In this case, we're getting 10.05 p.m. because that's what that is here in the string.

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:24.460
So it's all very overwhelming.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:25.739
Like, where do we get these?

00:12:25.739 --> 00:12:27.140
You know, there's lots of them.

00:12:27.140 --> 00:12:29.580
We actually have a function in GT called info date style.

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:31.140
We can just run that.

00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:39.979
And what it does is it gives us a table of all the different format names that you can use here in date style.

00:12:39.979 --> 00:12:41.900
And it gives you an example with an input.

00:12:41.900 --> 00:12:46.539
And so you just look down and see what, you know, the different outputs are for the same date.

00:12:46.539 --> 00:12:47.419
So really kind of cool.

00:12:47.419 --> 00:12:52.739
You just got to copy and paste this, put it into here and you're off essentially.

00:12:52.739 --> 00:12:56.500
So same sort of thing for the time styles because it's a separate function.

00:12:56.500 --> 00:12:59.539
It's got a separate function for the info table right here.

00:12:59.539 --> 00:13:02.500
Great. So you see HMP is this right here.

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:06.299
And this is the example formatted time.

00:13:06.299 --> 00:13:07.739
So that's all great.

00:13:07.739 --> 00:13:10.059
We also have this other function called format date time.

00:13:10.059 --> 00:13:11.219
It has tons of power.

00:13:11.219 --> 00:13:20.419
It allows you to actually use a formatting string and to style your date time strings just the way you want them.

00:13:20.419 --> 00:13:23.260
So we can use date styles and we can use time styles together.

00:13:23.260 --> 00:13:26.820
And it will separately format those two parts and give you an output.

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:29.299
So let's actually see it in practice.

00:13:29.299 --> 00:13:33.299
So we get this. We get the date and then we get the time just after that.

00:13:33.299 --> 00:13:40.539
Okay. A cool new thing that was added in the latest release is that you can have locales.

00:13:40.539 --> 00:13:45.299
So say for instance, you want a time in a different language.

00:13:45.299 --> 00:13:46.460
So you can use the same input.

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:53.059
You just have to use locale and then the name of the locale and you will get the output date in that language,

00:13:53.059 --> 00:13:56.340
like basically specific for that locale.

00:13:56.340 --> 00:13:58.659
So that's a new thing.

00:13:58.659 --> 00:14:06.500
So another new thing is we have a totally different way of formatting dates and times with this new type of format string.

00:14:06.500 --> 00:14:12.739
You can still use the old type that hasn't changed, but it will detect whether using this other type, which is called CLDR.

00:14:12.739 --> 00:14:16.619
So it basically has more fields for formatting dates and times.

00:14:16.619 --> 00:14:17.500
It's way more flexible.

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:23.900
It has tons of support for time zones as well if you have that in your input, which is totally supported here.

00:14:23.900 --> 00:14:28.260
But I just want to say that this is a great way of formatting really advanced dates and times.

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:31.260
So that's one example here.

00:14:31.260 --> 00:14:32.940
And it's fully localizable.

00:14:32.940 --> 00:14:42.179
So we can just put the locale here and it just switches it to the Dutch version of that date time, which is really cool.

00:14:42.179 --> 00:14:45.020
So learning about this is actually kind of difficult.

00:14:45.020 --> 00:14:49.619
It's almost like you need a crash course in this whole thing.

00:14:49.619 --> 00:15:01.260
But that's no problem because we actually have documentation and it's really extensive in the project website for GT.

00:15:01.260 --> 00:15:14.739
And it's available at gt.rstudio.com and particularly look at the reference section and you'll find that the daytime formatting functions and the documentation is super huge and there's tons of help on all this stuff.

00:15:14.739 --> 00:15:18.099
So that's all I have for the new enhancements and features in GT.

00:15:18.099 --> 00:15:19.099
This is a great script.

00:15:19.099 --> 00:15:29.419
It allows you to sort of like test out things that are new and we'll have this script available for everybody to use and the link to it will be available in the video notes.

00:15:29.419 --> 00:15:36.380
If you have any questions about GT, you can always ask me in the issues in GT, which is at the GitHub repository for the package.

